ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: 1. Where do you live?
Notes: 1= A - At home with parents.; 2= B - In a university residence hall.; 3= C - In a fraternity/sorority house.; 4= D - In a house/apartment; -9999= Do not wish to answer

ElementDescription: 2. How are your living expenses (rent, food, entertainment, etc.) paid?
Notes: 1= A - Mostly by parents=; 2= B - Mostly by scholarship= parents pay the rest.; 3= C - Mostly by yourself; 4= D - Mostly by scholarship= you pay the rest; -9999= Do not wish to answer

ElementDescription: 1. Where do you get your money?
Notes: 1= A - Allowance from parents/caregivers; 2= B - Gifts; 3= C -You have a regular job; 4= D - You work odd jobs; 5= E - Other

ElementDescription: 1. Where do you get your money? Specify "Other"
2. How are your school expenses (notebooks, supplies, etc.) and clothing paid?
Notes: 1= A - Mostly by parents/caregivers; 2= B - By yourself and by your parents/caregivers; 3= C - Mostly by yourself

ElementDescription: 3. Who pays for other things you use (cell phone, games, movies, sports, music)?
Notes: 1= A - Mostly by parents/caregivers; 2= B - By yourself and by your parents/caregivers; 3= C - Mostly by yourself

ElementDescription: 4. During an average week, how often do you eat at a restaurant?
Notes: 1= A - Never eat out; 2= B - Less than 3 times; 3= C - 3-7 times; 4= D - Almost all meals

ElementDescription: 5. When you eat out, how much do you usually spend?
Notes: 1= A - Your parents/caregivers usually pay when you eat out; 2= B - Less than $6.50; 3= C - $6.50 to $13; 4= D - More than $13

ElementDescription: 6. How often do you have pocket money to buy simple things?
Notes: 1= A - Never; 2= B - Sometimes= but there are days when you are broke.; 3= C - Usually; 4= D - Always

ElementDescription: 7. On weekends, if you want to, how often do you have money to go out?
Notes: 1= A - Never; 2= B - Sometimes= but sometimes you have to stay home.; 3= C - Usually; 4= D - Always

ElementDescription: 8. Are you employed?
Notes: 1= A - Yes; 2= B - Yes= by family or neighbors; 3= C - No. You don't have a job but you are looking for one; 4= D - No. You don't have a job and you are not looking for one.
